Figure 5 depicts the XRD patterns of CdS films annealed in vacuum, N2, and air. As shown, besides the diffraction peaks of FTO substrate, all the diffraction peaks can be aligned to hexagonal CdS structure (JCPDF, no. 80-6). This XRD results confirm that the environment of annealing treatment shows no significant effect on the crystal structure of CdS. However, it is noteworthy that after air-annealing treatment, an additional peak corresponding to CdO can be observed (Fig. 5c). The formation of CdO can be attributed to the oxidation of CdS when the film is annealed in air atmosphere. Besides, the XRD peaks of N2 annealed CdS films become narrower, suggesting an improved crystalline quality. Based on Debye–Scherrer’s formula, the average crystallite size (D) of vacuum and N2 annealed CdS film is calculated: D=kλβ(hkl)cosθ.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
